{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"15146769-20df-40f3-a1eb-e76af4b71c19","content":"You're on MSTest 3.8.2 which supports constructor injection. Here's the recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests : IAsyncInitialization, IAsyncCleanup\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n\n    // Constructor injection for TestContext (MSTest 3.3+)\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n        // Synchronous init here (lightweight setup only)\n    }\n\n    // Async initialization (replaces [TestInitialize] for async work)\n    public Task InitializeAsync()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Async init running\");\n        // await your async setup (DB connections, HTTP clients, etc.)\n        return Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    // Async cleanup (replaces [TestCleanup] for async work)\n    public Task CleanupAsync()\n    {\n        return Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void SampleTest()\n    {\n        Assert.IsNotNull(_testContext);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **Constructor injection** of `TestContext` requires MSTest ≥ 3.3. You have 3.8.2, so you're good.\n- **`IAsyncInitialization`** runs before each test (async equivalent of `[TestInitialize]`).\n- **`IAsyncCleanup`** runs after each test (async equivalent of `[TestCleanup]`).\n- The constructor handles sync setup; `InitializeAsync` handles anything requiring `await`.\n- The old `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property approach still works but constructor injection is now preferred.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0c81ae9b-cf89-42f7-8aeb-9cf09fa5244f","outputTokens":416,"requestId":"E44C:2843AB:3F67CA8:459180B:6A02FB73"},"id":"40d04da4-10f2-4f9c-a96b-3b497f4a5bcf","timestamp":"2026-05-12T10:05:50.246Z","parentId":"d4306c04-853d-4580-98a1-a9d1a09e1340"}
